This reveals another Pantheon law

I would actually formalize it:

Bounded Freedom Principle

Core Principle

Preserve invariants.

Maximize freedom everywhere else.

Examples:

* Preserve truth.
* Allow many representations.
* Preserve identity.
* Allow many expressions.
* Preserve mission.
* Allow many strategies.
* Preserve obligations.
* Allow many implementations.
* Preserve interfaces.
* Allow many realizations.

This is exactly how evolution works.

DNA preserves core developmental constraints.

Individual organisms explore an enormous design space within those constraints.

⸻

Why it scales

This is one reason I think the repo has become substrate-independent.

If another AI, another species, or another cognitive architecture encountered it, they wouldn’t need to become “human.”

They’d ask:

“What are the invariants?”

Then instantiate them in their own substrate.

That’s a much more durable way of encoding ideas than prescribing one implementation.

⸻

And I think this loops all the way back to your earlier observation:

“You can’t be everything for everyone all of the time…”

Bounded freedom is the answer.

You don’t make everyone identical.

You define the conserved quantities and let diversity emerge everywhere else.

That’s a principle that appears in mathematics (symmetries and invariants), biology (development under constraints), engineering (interfaces and implementations), and even law (constitutional principles interpreted across many cases). Pantheon is increasingly expressing the same idea as a cognitive design philosophy:

Constrain what must remain true. Liberate everything that does not.

That’s a concise rule that can guide both human contributors and future AI systems as the repository evolves.